<div class="bg-zinc-950 text-zinc-100">
  <.marketing_nav current_user={@current_user} current={:docs} />

  <section class="py-16 sm:py-24">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 lg:px-8">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-brand-400">Compare</p>
      <.marketing_heading tag="h1" scale={:hero} class="mt-2">
        Why not just give the LLM SSH?
      </.marketing_heading>
      <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-8 text-zinc-400 text-pretty">
        The honest answer: you can. Some people do. It works on the days it works.
        Here's what changes when it doesn't.
      </p>

      <h2 class="mt-12 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50 text-balance">
        Both approaches run real commands
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
        emisar isn't a sandbox. When the runner executes <code>nomad job revert</code>, it really rolls back the deploy — exactly like
        SSH would. The difference is what happens <em>before</em> exec, and what's
        left <em>after</em>.
      </p>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50 text-balance">Side-by-side</h2>
      <%!-- One data list, two layouts: a table on md+, stacked cards on mobile, so
        the 3-way comparison reads without a horizontal scroll on phones. --%>
      <% rows = [
        {"What can the LLM run?", "Anything in the user's shell",
         "Only declared actions; everything else rejected"},
        {"What are the args?", "Free-text command line",
         "Typed, validated, redacted at the boundary"},
        {"What actually ran?", "Whatever was on PATH that day",
         "Content-addressed pack — the runner recomputes the SHA-256 and blocks changed contents until an admin re-trusts"},
        {"Approvals?", "Human-in-the-loop in chat — easy to skip",
         "Policy gates with approver email + audit; skipping means a policy change, itself audited"},
        {"Audit trail?", "Whatever lands in .bash_history + Slack scrollback",
         "Hash-chained JSONL on host, mirrored to cloud"},
        {"Output redaction?", "None — passwords leak into chat logs",
         "20+ patterns (bearer/JWT, AWS/GitHub/Slack keys, secret assignments) masked on the host before egress"},
        {"Lateral movement?", "SSH key on the model's box ≈ key everywhere",
         "Per-runner token + per-user runner scopes every API key inherits — revoke the user, every key they minted shrinks"},
        {"Recovery story?", "“Read the chat scrollback and the logs and hope”",
         "emisar audit verify + replay every dispatched envelope"}
      ] %>

      <%!-- Desktop: the comparison table --%>
      <div class="mt-4 hidden overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-zinc-900 md:block">
        <table class="w-full text-sm">
          <thead class="bg-zinc-950/80 text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-zinc-500">
            <tr>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-medium">Concern</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-medium">Raw SSH</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-brand-300">emisar action pack</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-zinc-900 text-zinc-300">
            <tr :for={{concern, raw, emisar} <- rows} class="hover:bg-zinc-900/30">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 align-top font-medium text-zinc-100">{concern}</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 align-top text-zinc-400">{raw}</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 align-top text-zinc-300">{emisar}</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <%!-- Mobile: one card per concern, the emisar answer accented --%>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 md:hidden">
        <div
          :for={{concern, raw, emisar} <- rows}
          class="rounded-xl border border-zinc-900 bg-zinc-950/60 p-4"
        >
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-zinc-100">{concern}</p>
          <div class="mt-3 space-y-3 text-sm">
            <div>
              <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-zinc-500">
                Raw SSH
              </p>
              <p class="mt-0.5 text-zinc-400">{raw}</p>
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-2 border-brand-500/40 pl-3">
              <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-brand-400">
                emisar
              </p>
              <p class="mt-0.5 text-zinc-300">{emisar}</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50 text-balance">
        When raw SSH is the right answer
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
        Single-operator side projects, throwaway environments, dev clusters
        you can wipe. The cost of declaring an action pack only pays back
        when there's <em>another human</em> who needs to audit, override, or
        recover from the AI's decisions.
      </p>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50 text-balance">When it isn't</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
        Production. Anything regulated. Anything where post-incident your
        VP of Engineering will ask "what did the model do, exactly, and on
        whose authority?". That's the question raw SSH can't answer without
        a forensic budget. emisar makes the answer a query.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-12 rounded-xl border border-brand-900/40 bg-brand-950/20 p-5 text-sm text-zinc-300">
        Try it: install the runner from the <.link
          navigate={~p"/docs/quickstart"}
          class="text-brand-400 hover:text-brand-300"
        >quickstart</.link>, declare one action you'd otherwise SSH for, and point your model at
        it. The
        <.link navigate={~p"/pricing"} class="text-brand-400 hover:text-brand-300">
          free tier
        </.link>
        covers 3 runners — no credit card.
      </div>

      <div class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap gap-x-6 gap-y-3 border-t border-zinc-900 pt-8 text-sm">
        <.link
          navigate={~p"/docs/security-model"}
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 font-medium text-brand-400 hover:text-brand-300"
        >
          How the trust boundary works <.icon name="hero-arrow-right" class="h-3.5 w-3.5" />
        </.link>
        <.link
          navigate={~p"/docs/connect-an-llm"}
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 font-medium text-brand-400 hover:text-brand-300"
        >
          Connect your model <.icon name="hero-arrow-right" class="h-3.5 w-3.5" />
        </.link>
        <.link
          navigate={~p"/use-cases/cassandra-ops"}
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 font-medium text-brand-400 hover:text-brand-300"
        >
          See it on a Cassandra incident <.icon name="hero-arrow-right" class="h-3.5 w-3.5" />
        </.link>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <.marketing_cta
    headline="Stop handing AI agents raw SSH."
    subcopy="The same real commands — declared, policy-gated, approval-checked, and journaled. Recovery you're not betting your weekend on."
    secondary_label="Read the quickstart"
    secondary_path={~p"/docs/quickstart"}
  />

  <.marketing_footer />
</div>
